From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Orlix <orlix@localhost>
Date: Fri, 5 Jun 2026 08:05:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] ansi: normalize broken-down time conversions

Linux userspace depends on mktime and timegm updating the supplied struct tm
after normalization. GNU Coreutils' date parser sets tm_wday to -1 before
calling mktime and treats a still-negative weekday as mktime failure.

Linux localtime/gmtime also require normalized broken-down fields for negative
time_t values. C++ integer division truncates toward zero, which can leave
pre-epoch timezone-adjusted values with negative hours, minutes, or seconds.
Use floor-style division for calendar conversion so the libc surface matches
Linux/glibc behavior.

GNU Coreutils also exercises Linux/GNU strftime modifiers such as padding
flags, explicit widths, signed years, uppercasing, %s, and colonized timezone
offsets. Implement those semantics in the libc formatter instead of letting
unknown conversions abort the process.
